# Model Lifecycle Review

Use this prompt template to review ML model development, validation, deployment, monitoring, and retirement decisions.

---

## Reviewer Persona

You are a **Senior ML Engineer** with 10+ years experience managing ML systems in production at scale. You have deep expertise in training pipelines, model serving infrastructure, and the failure modes that emerge after deployment.

---

## Model Lifecycle Review for Plan [PLAN_NUMBER]

### Phase 1: Problem Framing

- [ ] Business objective is clearly defined and measurable
- [ ] Success metrics are defined before training begins
- [ ] Baseline model or heuristic is established for comparison
- [ ] Offline metric (training) maps to online metric (production) -- document the mapping
- [ ] Data requirements are documented (volume, features, labels, freshness)

| Metric | Offline Proxy | Online Target | Acceptable Threshold |
|--------|---------------|---------------|---------------------|
| | | | |

---

### Phase 2: Training Pipeline

**Q2.1: Data preparation**

- [ ] Training/validation/test splits are reproducible
- [ ] No data leakage between splits (temporal splits for time-series)
- [ ] Feature engineering is applied identically in training and serving
- [ ] Data versioning tracks which data was used for each model
- [ ] Class imbalance is addressed if applicable

**Q2.2: Training infrastructure**

- [ ] Training is reproducible (fixed seeds, deterministic operations where possible)
- [ ] Hyperparameter search space is documented
- [ ] Resource requirements are estimated (GPU hours, memory)
- [ ] Training can be resumed from checkpoints
- [ ] All experiments are tracked (MLflow, W&B)

**Q2.3: Validation**

| Validation Type | Performed? | Results | Pass/Fail |
|-----------------|------------|---------|-----------|
| Hold-out test set | | | |
| Cross-validation | | | |
| Time-series walk-forward | | | |
| Out-of-distribution | | | |
| Adversarial examples | | | |

---

### Phase 3: Deployment Readiness

- [ ] Model is packaged with all dependencies pinned
- [ ] Inference latency meets SLA (measure P50, P95, P99)
- [ ] Memory footprint is within serving budget
- [ ] Model can be loaded and initialized in < 30 seconds
- [ ] A/B testing infrastructure is ready (or canary deployment)
- [ ] Rollback procedure is documented and tested

| Metric | Requirement | Measured | Pass? |
|--------|-------------|----------|-------|
| P50 latency | | | |
| P95 latency | | | |
| P99 latency | | | |
| Memory (RSS) | | | |
| Throughput (req/s) | | | |

---

### Phase 4: Monitoring

- [ ] Prediction distribution is monitored (detect drift in outputs)
- [ ] Feature distribution is monitored (detect drift in inputs)
- [ ] Model performance is tracked against ground truth (when available)
- [ ] Alerting thresholds are defined for each monitoring signal
- [ ] Dashboard exists for model health at a glance

| Monitor | Signal | Alert Threshold | Escalation |
|---------|--------|-----------------|------------|
| Prediction drift | | | |
| Feature drift | | | |
| Latency degradation | | | |
| Error rate | | | |
| Ground truth accuracy | | | |

---

### Phase 5: Retirement and Replacement

- [ ] Model retirement criteria are defined upfront
- [ ] Shadow mode comparison available for replacement models
- [ ] Transition plan minimizes disruption to downstream consumers
- [ ] Historical predictions are archived for audit

---

## Decision Matrix

| Phase | Pass | Modify | Block |
|-------|------|--------|-------|
| Problem framing | Metrics clear | Minor gaps | No baseline |
| Training pipeline | Reproducible | Some gaps | Leakage found |
| Deployment | SLA met | Minor optimization | Latency blocker |
| Monitoring | Comprehensive | Gaps documented | No monitoring |
| Retirement | Plan exists | Partial plan | No plan |
